231":"1231","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","Notton, Yorkshire, England":"Notton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Samlesbury, Lancashire, England":"Samlesbury, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Notton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William De Notton II was born in 1190, in Notton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1231, in Samlesbury, Lancashire, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1190–1231":"1190–1231","1200–1278":"1200–1278","1220–1275":"1220–1275","1190":"1190","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","1231":"1231","1275":"1275","1220":"1220","Notton, Yorkshire, England":"Notton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancash